Blogdown Tutorial

In this tutorial, Im going to walk you through how to use GitHub to host a static Hugo blog using RStudio the R package {blogdown}.

This tutorial assumes that you have set-up a GitHub account and a personal webpage (e.g., USERNAME.github.io). It also assumes that you have downloaded GitHub desktop and have linked your sites repository there. If you havent done these steps, be sure to do so prior to beginning this tutorial.

Here are the steps for the tutorial:

  1. Installing the {blogdown} package.
  2. Preparing a local home for your blog.
  3. Select and install blog template.
  4. Customize and configure your blog.
  5. Creating a new post.
  6. Loading it onto GitHub

1. Installing the {blogdown} package.

Open up a new R script in RStudio. Install the blogdown package from CRAN. (If you want to install it from GitHub, you can do so via the {devtools} or {remotes} packages.)

#Install from CRAN
install.packages("blogdown")

#Install from GitHub via devtools
devtools::install_github("rstudio/blogdown")

#Install from GitHub via remotes
remotes::install_github("rstudio/blogdown")

2. Prepare a local home for your blog.

Your blog will ultimately be on the web for everyone to see! But some people, me included, like to base what appears online off of a version stored locally on their computer.

Using File Explorer (or Finder, if youre on a Mac), set up a new, empty folder to store your blog. For this tutorial, Ive done so in a file on my D drive called Blog Tutorial. But you can save yours anywhere! In your documents, on your desktop, on dropboxwhatever you want! (For what its worth, I save my actual blog on Dropbox so I can work on it across devices.)

Go back to RStudio after setting up the directory. Then set your working directory to the path of the folder you just set up. (If youre on a Mac and dont know how to look up the file path of a folder, Id suggest reading this tutorial. If you dont feel like extra reading, you can also set your directory using RStudios point-and-click interface by clicking on Session at the top, going to Set Working Directory and then clicking on Choose Directory.)

# Setting working directory

setwd("D:/Blog Tutorial/")

3. Select and install your blog template

Go to themes.gohugo.io/tags/blog. It should look something like this:



For this tutorial, Im going to use the Coder template:

Once youve selected your template of choice, go to the blogs github homepage. Usually, clicking on Download on the sites page will take you there. (Sometimes you may have to google <TEMPLATE NAME> hugo githubalthough this doesnt happen often, in my experience.)

Once youre there, copy the user name and repository in the address bar. For Coder, this is luizdepra/hugo-coder, as highlighted in blue in the screen-cap below.



With this copied, return to your RStudio session. Use the {blogdown} function new_site and copy the user name and repository information (in quotes).

blogdown::new_site(theme = "luizdepra/hugo-coder")

4. Customize and configure your blog.

After youve installed the site into your working directory, RStudio may open a couple of windows. the first is a sample RMarkdown document, usually titled something like 2015-07-23-r-markdown.rmd. It would look something like this:

You can safely ignore that for now.

It will also often open up a version of your site in the viewer pane.

It may also open up a file titled config.toml. If it does, great! If not, go to the file that youve assigned as your working directory and open the config.toml file in a text-editing program like Notepad, Notepad++, or Atom. (Not to be confused with opening it up in a word processor like Word.)

Each sites toml is going to be a little different. However, the things youre going to be looking to change are things that are usually located near [params]. These include things like author, blog name, title, and description. These are the most important ones to look out for. Go ahead and change them to whatever you want. Heres what it looks like after I edited a few of the parameters.

Note: You dont have to just stick with the same stuff as your theme if you dont want to. There are bunch of different ways you could customize your site via the toml and the accompanying hmtl and javascript. I usually have luck looking for scss files, but itll take some pocking, prodding, and googling.

5. Writing a New Post

Once youve made all the changes that you want, make sure that youre in the same working directory as your site. Then go to the addins button near the top of your RStudio pane. Click new post. A RMarkdown document will open up. You can write in this as you would any other Rmarkdown document (and as you have been doing all of the assignments.)

Once youre finished writing, be sure to save it. Then enter the command blogdown::build_site() into the console (or into your R script, so long as you run it.)

6.

From here, open your GitHub desktop. Access the repository that you used to build your site (the one with the Hello world! html file, ending in github.io.) Either enter ctrl+shift+f or cmd+shift+f (depending on if youre using either Windows or Mac), which will bring you to the GitHub file directory.

Using either file explorer or finder, go to the local directory where you have saved your blog. Open the folder called public. Copy all of the items inside the public folder. Delete the Hello World file from the GitHub desktop directory. Then paste all the contents of the public folder into your github.io repository. Push the changes to your GitHub account. Wait 5-10 minutes. Your site should now be live and ready for you to write new posts!

You will have to do steps 5 and 6 every time you write a new post. However, most of the work is honestly finding and customizing the site. I hope this helps!
